TheÂ black snub-nosed monkeyÂ (Rhinopithecus bieti) is anÂ endangered speciesÂ endemicÂ toÂ China, where it is known to the locals as the black golden hair monkey (é»‘é‡‘ä¸çŒ´). It is threatened byÂ habitat loss but today thanks to the efforts of @nature_org the number of these monkeys is raising. New jobs have been created thanks to the creation on a National Park and now local people are on the front line in the conservation of this species.
This is an example of how is it possible to successfully involve people's that once threatened the wildlife.

The black snub-nosed monkey was almost completely unknown until the 1990s. The fact that no single zoo outside China has ever kept the black snub-nosed monkey in captivity has contributed to the enigmatic status of this species. The black snub-nosed monkey lives in one of the most extreme environments of any nonhuman primate. The highest recorded altitude of a group of this species is 4700 m.Â The black snub-nosed monkey lives in very large super-groups which are made up of single-male core families or harems.The monkey moves fast and far in a cohesive group and covers vast areas in search of lichens and other seasonally available food items.

I will post more pictures in the next days.
A big thanks also to @kingstontechnology for providing technical support.

One of the most impressive place I've ever been to. Yuanyang Rice Terraces, in China, areÂ the Hani ethnic minority's masterpieceÂ of ingenuity. In unique shapes and sizes with thousands of years of history, they form a mosaic of colorful and breathtaking landscapes of natural beauty.
Known as aÂ "land sculpture", the terraced fields have been officially acknowledged by UNESCO as a World Cultural and Natural Heritage Site. There are three popular scenic areas: Duoyishu, Bada, and Laohuzui.
In my trips I visited some rice terraces in different countries like Sapa in Vietnam but none of them are as nearly as spectacular as YuanYang. If you want to visit this UNESCO site but you don't feel like organizing the trip by yourself (traveling in China is not easy) than I suggest you contact @woytravel. They speak English and have a lot of experience. A big thank you also to @raymasterscamerafilters and their amazing filters. If you want to take great landscapes pictures than you should try them.
